title: Don't look for illegal characters in escaped identifiers

commits.message:
Don't look for illegal characters in escaped identifiers

There are cases when escaping an illegal identifier does not make
it legal, e.g.:

class `My.Class` // Doesn't compile

But in many cases escaping an identifier does make it legal:

enum class MyEnum {
  `Foo.Bar` // Compiles
}

Since KotlinPoet is not a compiler, we don't want to over-police
illegal identifier checks, so we'll assume every escaped
identifier is valid, that way we don't block correctly escaped
identifiers.

Fixes #2203
Add test for manually escaped identifiers

title: Fix annotation array args with annotation elements

commits.message:
Fix annotation array args with annotation elements

Previously, AnnotationSpec.Builder.memberForValue() did not
correctly handle annotation instances inside annotation array
parameters. For example, given:

  annotation class AnnotationC(val value: String)
  annotation class AnnotationD(
    val s: Array<AnnotationC> = [AnnotationC("foo")]
  )

When generating code from existing annotation instances using
reflection, KotlinPoet would produce the following invalid
Kotlin code:

  @AnnotationD(
    s = arrayOf(@com.example.AnnotationC("foo")),
  )
  public class Taco

With this change, annotation values in arrays are handled by
delegating to AnnotationSpec.get(), producing valid Kotlin code.
Related test functions have also been updated accordingly.

Remove needless withJava

The multiplatform plugin now configures Java automatically.
